Kasumi

For clarification, this world does not have anthros integrated into society, but myths and legends do exist. Also, there are more sisters, but I haven't thought about them yet.

>>44411923
Not sure why your original post is gone now. I had a couple comments. Going to limit it to a couple general observations.

Kitsune with a lot of tails are very powerful. A seven tailed kitsune is already flirting with godhood. Consider scaling that back a bit. Unless you think you want overpowered characters for whatever your reasons. Possibility: the eldest sister has five tails, but is on the verge of gaining her sixth; there's some plot could be involved with her reaching a new power level. Some kitsune kill other kitsune and steal their tails to gain power, in case you want to consider a dark angle.

This option could place the youngest sister at two tails and the married one with three or four. Still quite a powerful youkai. An option here is to have the youngest sister on the verge of gaining her third tail and drop that plotline for the other sisters. Given the youngest is shy/inexperienced/virgin etc., it makes more sense that she still hasn't quite leveled up yet. A three-tailed kitsune has been around and Done Some Shit™, possibly even including having had her first child already. Passing out of her virginity could be one significant trigger to boost her to the next level.

The married sister could be interesting, but for a porn piece you have to make a decision about her and her husband being monogamous and how that will affect their presence in any storylines. This pairing has the advantage of pursuing a breeding plotline. And, since there are other sisters, one or more of them can be introduced if a husband-waifur plotline becomes a limited vehicle for porn.

Their mom could possibly be an eight-tail, if she's a pretty powerful matriarch with strong influence for their clan for the entire region they live in/originate from. Wouldn't be any sin for her to "only" be a seven-tail. Her eldest daughter already gaining her sixth could be relevant as to how ambitious/powerful the daughter is, also setting the stage a bit for some darkness.

This is why there's a bit of discussion about kitsune. As said >>44414293 >>44414409, illusion is no small power to turn your nose up at. The strength of an individual and how powerful they make the illusion is important, and can be reality-bending by a very powerful and skilled caster.

In addition to that, a known kitsune power is the ability to transform themselves into other forms. At the lower levels it might be just an illusion, but they go beyond illusion at some point and physically transform. The really powerful kitsune can transform other creatures.

Among youkai, kitsune are considered the equivalent of apex predators. They can consume other spirits for power. As mentioned, the most powerful amongst them become candidates to ascend as divine beings, actual gods and goddesses. Even in Japanese mythology, not a common occurrence. They have broad power to accomplish general manifestation of their will through their spiritual strength when they get near this level, although it can come at great cost to themselves (including their own death) if they fail or overextend.

Illusions & fire would be common at the lower levels, maybe even all a two-tail might accomplish (apart from manifesting their human form). However, those abilities escalate on a non-linear scale as they gain tails.

Kitsune fear very little, especially when they hit the five-tail tier and transcend it.

Anonymous Sun 02 Jan 2022 05:35:59 No.44418094 Report
Quoted By: >>44418392
>>44417364
>tanuki suppose to be rivals with them with the strongest being on par with stronger kitsune
Not that I'm aware of. Not in a general sense. There may be stories of specific individuals on either side that reached godhood and competed against each other. But, tanuki are generally a mid-powerful creature. Scary to humans, and the old ones are renowned for being especially tricky and potentially dangerous to humans. As far as rivaling kitsune, I'm more aware of tanuki dealing with kitsune by hiding from them. It's a bit tough because I only get these stories through what trickles into English, and I don't recall direct fighting between tanuki & kitsune. Just, tanuki don't usually scare humans, they're almost comical and not usually thought of as gods running a large and prosperous shrine. More like drunken little forest grannies that are happy to torment humans for fun, or to protect the forest.

> also there isn't really any lore about any determining things that factor their strength like an increase number of tails.
Nope. There is substantial lore around the number of tails a kitsune has and the amount of power they have. Single tailed kitsune are barely more than wild foxes, twin-tailed annoying tricksters (who can also be tricked) with enough power to walk among humans with the illusion of a human form. By the time they get to five tails they can spirit away human children and women into the spirit realm, perform physical transformation, other pretty high-powered magic. At this point hey can have their own shrines, with entire towns providing tribute in hopes of that kitsune granting prosperity to the region with its powers. From that level and upward they can become gods/goddesses. Powerfully good or frightening evil/malevolent.

It isn't that the tails give them power, it's that they gain more tails as they become more powerful. Tails can also manifest abstractly as light & energy, not just physical body parts.
